    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The linear scale below was used to measure the distance between two mountain peaks on a map. The distance between the two peaks is <m>15 \textbf{ cm}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
               (a) Write the linear scale in ratio form.
            </p>
            <p>
                (b) If the distance between the two peaks is <m>15 \textbf{ cm}</m>, what is the actual distance between the two peaks in km?
            </p>
            <p>
                (c) If the distance between two other mountain peaks along the same range is <m>60 \textbf{ km}</m>, determine the scale of the distance between them on the map.
            </p>
             <image>
                <latex-image label="Linear-Scale-mountain-peaks">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Draw alternating black and white rectangles
                        \foreach \i in {0,1,2,3} {
                        \ifodd\i
                            \fill[white] (\i,0) rectangle (\i+1,0.4);
                        \else
                            \fill[black] (\i,0) rectangle (\i+1,0.4);
                        \fi
                        }
                    
                        % Draw the border line at the top
                        \draw[thick] (0,0.4) -- (4,0.4);
                    
                        % Vertical tick at the end
                        \draw[thick] (4,0) -- (4,0.5);
                    
                        % Tick marks and labels
                        \foreach \i in {0,1,2,3,4} {
                        \draw[thick] (\i,0.4) -- (\i,0.5);
                        \node[anchor=north] at (\i,0) {\i};
                        }
                    
                        % Label
                        \node[anchor=west] at (4.1,0.2) {Kilometers};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
             </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                (a) From the scale bar: The length of each bar is 1cm. 
            </p>
            <p>
                The scale is <m>1 \textbf{ cm}</m> represents <m>1 \textbf{ km}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
               Convert 1 km to cm: 
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> 1 \text{km}= \amp  100\,000 \text{cm}</mrow>
                </md>
                Map:Actual distance = <m>1:100\,000 \textbf{ m}</m>

                So the ratio is <m>1:100,000</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                (b) The actual distance between the two peaks is <m>15 \textbf{ cm}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
             Using the ratio 1:100 000, we can find the actual distance:    
            </p>
            <p>   
                <md>
                    <mrow> 1:100\,000 = \amp 1\text{cm} represents 100\,000\,\text{cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> 15\,\text{cm} = \amp ? </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{15\,\text{cm } \times 100\,000 } {100\,000}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp {1\,500\,000}{100\,000}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 15\, \text{km} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                (c) The distance between the two peaks is <m>60 \textbf{ km}</m>. Using the same ratio <m>1:100\,000</m>, we can determine the map distance for an actual distance of <m>60 \textbf{ km}</m>:
                <md>
                    <mrow> 60 \,\text{km} =  \amp 60\,\text{cm} \times 100\,000</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 6\,000\,000 \text{cm} </mrow>
                    
                </md>
                Now divide by 100,000 to convert to map distance:
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{6\,000\,000 \text{cm} }{100\,000}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 60\, \text{cm}</mrow>
                </md>
                The distance the two other peeks within the same range is <m>60 \textbf{ cm}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example> 
